{"key":"processedPost-13807753","value":{"id":13807753,"first":13803704,"last":13810262,"when":1295381374,"utime":"01/18/11 10:09 PM","cleanedPost":"Cakes can be crumbled and mixed into a pasteurized bulk substrate material.&nbsp; However, it's best not to case cakes because you'll get no more yield than you would simply fruiting them as cakes.&nbsp; I think the biggest problem with this thread is some of you folks don't know the nomenclature.&nbsp; When people misuse the terms, it confuses the new folks.&nbsp; We seem to have a lot of new growers with the best of intentions giving advice to other new folks, and therein lies the problem.<br /><b>Spawning to bulk</b>:&nbsp; This means to break up cakes or grains and mix into a bulk substrate such as manure, straw, or coir, etc.<br /><b>Casing:</b>&nbsp; This means to lay colonized grains such as rye, millet, wild bird seed, etc., into a tray and cover with a non-nutritious layer such as peat/verm.&nbsp; In this case, the grains become the substrate. Little is to be gained by using cakes in this matter because they're already 2/3 vermiculite.<br />RR"}}